.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
.SS "\s-1MULTIPLE KEYWORDS\s0"
.IX Subsection "MULTIPLE KEYWORDS"
\&\fBgreple\fR has almost same function as Unix command \fBegrep\fR\|(1) but
search is done in a manner similar to Internet search engine.  For
example, next command print lines those contain all of `foo' and bar'
and `baz'.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \*(Aqfoo bar baz\*(Aq ...
.Ve
.PP
Each word can appear in any order and/or any place in the string.  So
this command find all of following texts.
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    foo bar baz
\&    baz bar foo
\&    the foo, bar and baz
.Ve
.PP
If you want to use \s-1OR\s0 syntax, prepend question mark (`?') on each
token, or use regular expression.
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    greple \*(Aqfoo bar baz ?yabba ?dabba ?doo\*(Aq
\&    greple \*(Aqfoo bar baz yabba|dabba|doo\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
This command will print lines those contains all of `foo', `bar' and
`baz' and one or more of `yabba', `dabba' or `doo'.
.PP
\&\s-1NOT\s0 operator can be specified by prefixing the token by minus sign
(`\-').  Next example will show lines those contain both `foo' and bar'
but none of `yabba', `dabba' or `doo'.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \*(Aqfoo bar \-yabba \-dabba \-doo\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
This can be written as this using \fB\-e\fR and \fB\-v\fR option.
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    greple \-e foo \-e bar \-v yabba \-v dabba \-v doo
\&    greple \-e foo \-e bar \-v \*(Aqyabba|dabba|doo\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
If `+' is placed to positive matching pattern, that pattern is marked
as required, and required match count is automatically set to the
number of required patterns.  So
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \*(Aq+foo bar baz\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
commands implicitly set the option \f(CW\*(C`\-\-need 1\*(C'\fR, and consequently print
all lines including `foo'.  In other words, it makes other patterns
optional.  If you want to search lines which includes `foo' and either
or both of `bar' and `baz', use like this:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    greple \*(Aq+foo bar baz\*(Aq \-\-need 2
\&    greple \*(Aq+foo bar baz\*(Aq \-\-need +1
.Ve
.SS "\s-1FLEXIBLE BLOCKS\s0"
.IX Subsection "FLEXIBLE BLOCKS"
Default data block \fBgreple\fR search and print is a line.  Using
\&\fB\-\-paragraph\fR (or \fB\-p\fR in short) option, series of text separated
by empty line is taken as a record block.  So next command will print
whole paragraph which contains the word `foo', `bar' and `baz'.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-p \*(Aqfoo bar baz\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
Option \fB\-\-all\fR takes whole file as a single block.  So next command
find files which contains these strings, and print the all contents.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-all \*(Aqfoo bar baz\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
Block also can be defined as a pattern.  Next command search and print
mail header, ignoring mail body text.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-block \*(Aq\eA(.+\en)+\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
You can also define arbitrary complex blocks by writing script.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-block \*(Aq&your_original_function\*(Aq ...
.Ve
.SS "\s-1MATCH AREA CONTROL\s0"
.IX Subsection "MATCH AREA CONTROL"
Using option \fB\-\-inside\fR and \fB\-\-outside\fR, you can specify text area
where the match should be occurred.  Next commands search only in mail
header and body area respectively.  In these cases, data block is not
changed, so print lines which contains the pattern in the specified
area.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-inside \*(Aq\eA(.+\en)+\*(Aq pattern
\&
\&    greple \-\-outside \*(Aq\eA(.+\en)+\*(Aq pattern
.Ve
.PP
Option \fB\-\-inside\fR/\fB\-\-outside\fR can be used repeatedly to enhance the
area to be matched.  There are similar option
\&\fB\-\-include\fR/\fB\-\-exclude\fR, but they are used to trim down the area.
.PP
Those four options also takes user defined function and any complex
region can be used.
.SS "\s-1LINE ACROSS MATCH\s0"
.IX Subsection "LINE ACROSS MATCH"
\&\fBgreple\fR search a given pattern across line boundaries.  This is
especially useful to handle Asian multi-byte text, more specifically
Japanese.  Japanese text can be separated by newline almost any place
in the text.  So the search pattern may spread out onto multiple
lines.
.PP
As for ascii word list, space character in the pattern matches any
kind of space including newline.  Next example will search the word
sequence of `foo', `bar' and 'baz', even they spread out to multiple
lines.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-e \*(Aqfoo bar baz\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
Option \fB\-e\fR is necessary because space is taken as a token separator
in the bare or \fB\-\-le\fR pattern.
.SS "\s-1MODULE AND CUSTOMIZATION\s0"
.IX Subsection "MODULE AND CUSTOMIZATION"
User can define default and original options in \fI~/.greplerc\fR.  Next
example enables colored output always, and define new option using
macro processing.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    option default \-\-color=always
\&
\&    define :re1 complex\-regex\-1
\&    define :re2 complex\-regex\-2
\&    define :re3 complex\-regex\-3
\&    option \-\-newopt \-\-inside :re1 \-\-exclude :re2 \-\-re :re3
.Ve
.PP
Specific set of function and option interface can be implemented as
module.  Modules are invoked by \fB\-M\fR option immediately after command
name.
.PP
For example, \fBgreple\fR does not have recursive search option, but it
can be implemented by \fB\-\-readlist\fR option which accept target file
list from standard input.  Using \fBfind\fR module, it can be written
like this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-Mfind . \-type f \-\- pattern
.Ve
.PP
Also \fBdig\fR module implements more complex search.  It can be used as
simple as this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-Mdig pattern \-\-dig .
.Ve
.PP
but this command is finally translated into following option list.
.PP
.Vb 5
\&    greple \-Mfind . ( \-name .git \-o \-name .svn \-o \-name RCS ) \-prune \-o 
\&        \-type f ! \-name .* ! \-name *,v ! \-name *~ 
\&        ! \-iname *.jpg ! \-iname *.jpeg ! \-iname *.gif ! \-iname *.png 
\&        ! \-iname *.tar ! \-iname *.tbz  ! \-iname *.tgz ! \-iname *.pdf 
\&        \-print \-\- pattern
.Ve
.SH "OPTIONS"
.IX Header "OPTIONS"
.SS "\s-1PATTERNS\s0"
.IX Subsection "PATTERNS"
If no specific option is given, \fBgreple\fR takes the first argument as
a search pattern specified by \fB\-\-le\fR option.  All of these patterns
can be specified multiple times.
.PP
Command itself is written in Perl, and any kind of Perl style regular
expression can be used in patterns.  See \fBperlre\fR\|(1) for detail.
.PP
Note that multiple line modifier (\f(CW\*(C`m\*(C'\fR) is set when executed, so put
\&\f(CW\*(C`(?\-m)\*(C'\fR at the beginning of regex if you want to explicitly disable
it.
.PP
Order of capture group in the pattern is not guaranteed.  Please avoid
to use direct index, and use relative or named capture group instead.
For example, repeated character can be written as \f(CW\*(C`(\ew)\eg{\-1}\*(C'\fR
or \f(CW\*(C`(?<c>\ew)\eg{c}\*(C'\fR.
.IP "\fB\-\-le\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "--le=pattern"
Treat the string as a collection of tokens separated by spaces.  Each
token is interpreted by the first character.  Token start with `\-'
means negative pattern, `?' means alternative, and `+' does required.
.Sp
Next example print lines which contains `foo' and `bar', and one or
more of `yabba' and 'dabba', and none of `baz' and `doo'.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-le=\*(Aqfoo bar \-baz ?yabba ?dabba \-doo\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
Multiple `?' preceded tokens are treated all mixed together.  That
means `?A|B ?C|D' is equivalent to `?A|B|C|D'.  If you want to mean
`(A or B) and (C or D)', use \s-1AND\s0 syntax instead: `A|B C|D'.
.Sp
This is the summary of start character for \fB\-\-le\fR option:
.Sp
.Vb 4
\&    +  Required pattern
\&    \-  Negative match pattern
\&    ?  Alternative pattern
\&    &  Function call (see next section)
.Ve
.IP "\fB\-\-le\fR=[\fB+\-\fR]\fB&\fR\fIfunction\fR" 7
.IX Item "--le=[+-]&function"
If the pattern start with ampersand (`&'), it is treated as a
function, and the function is called instead of searching pattern.
Function call interface is same as the one for block/region options.
.Sp
If you have a definition of \fIodd_line\fR function in you \fI.greplerc\fR,
which is described in this manual later, you can print odd number
lines like this:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-n \*(Aq&odd_line\*(Aq file
.Ve
.Sp
Required (\f(CW\*(C`+\*(C'\fR) and negative (\f(CW\*(C`\-\*(C'\fR) mark can be used for function
pattern.
.Sp
This version experimentally support callback function for each
pattern.  Region list returned by function can have two extra element
besides start/end position.  Third element is index.  Fourth element
is callback function pointer which is called to produce string to be
shown in command output.  Callback function takes four argument (start
position, end position, index, matched string) and returns replacement
string.
.IP "\fB\-e\fR \fIpattern\fR, \fB\-\-and\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "-e pattern, --and=pattern"
Specify positive match token.  Next two commands are equivalent.
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&    greple \*(Aqfoo bar baz\*(Aq
\&    greple \-e foo \-e bar \-e baz
.Ve
.Sp
First character is not interpreted, so next commands will search the
pattern `\-baz'.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-e \-baz
.Ve
.Sp
Space characters are treated specially by \fB\-e\fR and \fB\-v\fR options.
They are replaced by the pattern which matches any number of
white spaces including newline.  So the pattern can be expand to
multiple lines.  Next commands search the series of word `foo', `bar'
and `baz' even if they are separated by newlines.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-e \*(Aqfoo bar baz\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\fB\-r\fR \fIpattern\fR, \fB\-\-must\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "-r pattern, --must=pattern"
Specify required match token.  Next two commands are equivalent.
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&    greple \*(Aq+foo bar baz\*(Aq
\&    greple \-r foo \-e bar \-e baz
.Ve
.IP "\fB\-v\fR \fIpattern\fR, \fB\-\-not\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "-v pattern, --not=pattern"
Specify negative match token.  Because it does not affect to the bare
pattern argument, you can narrow down the search result like this.
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&    greple foo file
\&    greple foo file \-v bar
\&    greple foo file \-v bar \-v baz
.Ve
.IP "\fB\-\-re\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "--re=pattern"
Specify regular expression.  No special treatment for space and wide
characters.
.IP "\fB\-\-fe\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "--fe=pattern"
Specify fixed string pattern, like fgrep.
.IP "\fB\-i\fR, \fB\-\-ignore\-case\fR" 7
.IX Item "-i, --ignore-case"
Ignore case.
.IP "\fB\-\-need\fR=\fIn\fR" 7
.IX Item "--need=n"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-allow\fR=\fIn\fR" 7
.IX Item "--allow=n"
.PD
Option to compromise matching condition.  Option \fB\-\-need\fR specifies
the required match count, and \fB\-\-allow\fR the number of negative
condition to be overlooked.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-need=2 \-\-allow=1 \*(Aqfoo bar baz \-yabba \-dabba \-doo\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
Above command prints the line which contains two or more from `foo',
`bar' and `baz', and does not include more than one of `yabba',
`dabba' or `doo'.
.Sp
Using option \fB\-\-need\fR=\fI1\fR, \fBgreple\fR produces same result as \fBgrep\fR
command.
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&    grep   \-e foo \-e bar \-e baz
\&    greple \-e foo \-e bar \-e baz \-\-need=1
.Ve
.Sp
When the count \fIn\fR is negative value, it is subtracted from default
value.
.Sp
If the option \fB\-\-need=0\fR is specified and no pattern was found,
entire data is printed.  This is true even for required pattern.
.IP "\fB\-\-matchcount\fR=\fImin\fR[,\fImax\fR], \fB\-\-mc\fR=\fImin\fR[,\fImax\fR]" 7
.IX Item "--matchcount=min[,max], --mc=min[,max]"
When option \fB\-\-matchcount\fR is specified, only blocks which have given
match count will be shown.  Count \fImin\fR and \fImax\fR can be omitted,
and single number is taken as \fImin\fR.  Next commands print lines
including semicolons; 3 or more, exactly 3, and 3 or less,
respectively.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-matchcount=3 \*(Aq;\*(Aq file
\&
\&    greple \-\-matchcount=3,3 \*(Aq;\*(Aq file
\&
\&    greple \-\-matchcount=,3 \*(Aq;\*(Aq file
.Ve
.IP "\fB\-f\fR \fIfile\fR, \fB\-\-file\fR=\fIfile\fR" 7
.IX Item "-f file, --file=file"
Specify the file which contains search pattern.  When file contains
multiple lines, patterns on each lines are mixed together by \s-1OR\s0
context.
.Sp
Blank line and the line starting with sharp (#) character is ignored.
Two slashes (//) and following string are taken as a comment and
removed with preceding spaces.
.Sp
When multiple files specified, each file produces individual pattern.
.Sp
If the file name is followed by `[index]` string, it is treated as
specified by \fB\-\-select\fR option.  Next two commands are equivalent.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-f pattern_file\*(Aq[1,5:7]\*(Aq
\&
\&    greple \-f pattern_file \-\-select 1,5:7
.Ve
.Sp
See App::Greple::subst module.
.IP "\fB\-\-select\fR=\fIindex\fR" 7
.IX Item "--select=index"
When you want to choose specific pattern in the pattern file provided
by \fB\-f\fR option, use \fB\-\-select\fR option.  \fIindex\fR is number list
separated by comma (,) character and each numbers are interpreted by
Getopt::EX::Numbers module.  Take a look at the module document for
detail.
.Sp
Next command use 1st and 5,6,7th pattern in the file.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-f pattern_file \-\-select 1,5:7
.Ve
.SS "\s-1STYLES\s0"
.IX Subsection "STYLES"
.IP "\fB\-l\fR" 7
.IX Item "-l"
List filename only.
.IP "\fB\-c\fR, \fB\-\-count\fR" 7
.IX Item "-c, --count"
Print count of matched block.
.IP "\fB\-n\fR, \fB\-\-line\-number\fR" 7
.IX Item "-n, --line-number"
Show line number.
.IP "\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-no\-filename\fR" 7
.IX Item "-h, --no-filename"
Do not display filename.
.IP "\fB\-H\fR" 7
.IX Item "-H"
Display filename always.
.IP "\fB\-o\fR, \fB\-\-only\-matching\fR" 7
.IX Item "-o, --only-matching"
Print matched string only.  Newline character is printed after matched
string if it does not end with newline.  Use \fB\-\-no\-newline\fR option if
you don't need extra newline.
.IP "\fB\-m\fR \fIn\fR[,\fIm\fR], \fB\-\-max\-count\fR=\fIn\fR[,\fIm\fR]" 7
.IX Item "-m n[,m], --max-count=n[,m]"
Set the maximum count of blocks to be shown to \fIn\fR.
.Sp
Actually \fIn\fR and \fIm\fR are simply passed to perl splice function as
\&\fIoffset\fR and \fIlength\fR.  Works like this:
.Sp
.Vb 5
\&    greple \-m  10      # get first 10 blocks
\&    greple \-m   0,\-10  # get last 10 blocks
\&    greple \-m   0,10   # remove first 10 blocks
\&    greple \-m \-10      # remove last 10 blocks
\&    greple \-m  10,10   # remove 10 blocks from 10th (10\-19)
.Ve
.Sp
This option does not affect to search performance and command exit
status.
.Sp
Note that \fBgrep\fR command also has same option, but it's behavior is
different when invoked to multiple files.  \fBgreple\fR produces given
number of output for each files, while \fBgrep\fR takes it as a total
number of output.
.IP "\fB\-A\fR[\fIn\fR], \fB\-\-after\-context\fR[=\fIn\fR]" 7
.IX Item "-A[n], --after-context[=n]"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-B\fR[\fIn\fR], \fB\-\-before\-context\fR[=\fIn\fR]" 7
.IX Item "-B[n], --before-context[=n]"
.IP "\fB\-C\fR[\fIn\fR], \fB\-\-context\fR[=\fIn\fR]" 7
.IX Item "-C[n], --context[=n]"
.PD
Print \fIn\fR\-blocks before/after matched string.  The value \fIn\fR can be
omitted and the default is 2.  When used with \fB\-\-paragraph\fR or
\&\fB\-\-block\fR option, \fIn\fR means number of paragraph or block.
.Sp
Actually, these options expand the area of logical operation.  It
means
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-C1 \*(Aqfoo bar baz\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
matches following text.
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&    foo
\&    bar
\&    baz
.Ve
.Sp
Moreover
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-C1 \*(Aqfoo baz\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
also matches this text, because matching blocks around `foo' and `bar'
overlaps each other and makes single block.
.IP "\fB\-\-join\fR" 7
.IX Item "--join"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-joinby\fR=\fIstring\fR" 7
.IX Item "--joinby=string"
.PD
Convert newline character found in matched string to empty or specified
\&\fIstring\fR.  Using \fB\-\-join\fR with \fB\-o\fR (only-matching) option, you can
collect searching sentence list in one per line form.  This is
sometimes useful for Japanese text processing.  For example, next
command prints the list of \s-1KATAKANA\s0 words, including those spread
across multiple lines.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-ho \-\-join \*(Aq\ep{InKatakana}+(\en\ep{InKatakana}+)*\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
Space separated word sequence can be processed with \fB\-\-joinby\fR
option.  Next example prints all `for *something*' pattern in pod
documents within Perl script.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-Mperl \-\-pod \-ioe \*(Aq\ebfor \ew+\*(Aq \-\-joinby \*(Aq \*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\fB\-\-[no]newline\fR" 7
.IX Item "--[no]newline"
Since \fBgreple\fR can handle arbitrary blocks other than normal text
lines, they sometimes do not end with newline character.  Option \fB\-o\fR
makes similar situation.  In that case, extra newline is appended at
the end of block to be shown.  Option \fB\-\-no\-newline\fR disables this
behavior.
.IP "\fB\-\-filestyle\fR=\fIline\fR|\fIonce\fR|\fIseparate\fR, \fB\-\-fs\fR" 7
.IX Item "--filestyle=line|once|separate, --fs"
Default style is \fIline\fR, and \fBgreple\fR prints filename at the
beginning of each line.  Style \fIonce\fR prints the filename only once
at the first time.  Style \fIseparate\fR prints filename in the separate
line before each line or block.
.IP "\fB\-\-linestyle\fR=\fIline\fR|\fIseparate\fR, \fB\-\-ls\fR" 7
.IX Item "--linestyle=line|separate, --ls"
Default style is \fIline\fR, and \fBgreple\fR prints line numbers at the
beginning of each line.  Style \fIseparate\fR prints line number in the
separate line before each line or block.
.IP "\fB\-\-separate\fR" 7
.IX Item "--separate"
Shortcut for \fB\-\-filestyle\fR=\fIseparate\fR \fB\-\-linestyle\fR=\fIseparate\fR.
This is convenient to use block mode search and visiting each location
from supporting tool, such as Emacs.
.IP "\fB\-\-format\fR \fB\s-1LABEL\s0\fR=\fIformat\fR" 7
.IX Item "--format LABEL=format"
Define the format string of line number (\s-1LINE\s0) and file name (\s-1FILE\s0) to
be displayed.  Default is:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    \-\-format LINE=\*(Aq%d:\*(Aq
\&
\&    \-\-format FILE=\*(Aq%s:\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
Format string is passed to \f(CW\*(C`sprintf\*(C'\fR function.  Tab character can be
expressed as \f(CW\*(C`\et\*(C'\fR.
.Sp
Next example will show line numbers in five digits with tab space:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    \-\-format LINE=\*(Aq%05d\et\*(Aq
.Ve
.SS "\s-1FILES\s0"
.IX Subsection "FILES"
.IP "\fB\-\-glob\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "--glob=pattern"
Get files matches to specified pattern and use them as a target files.
Using \fB\-\-chdir\fR and \fB\-\-glob\fR makes easy to use \fBgreple\fR for fixed
common job.
.IP "\fB\-\-chdir\fR=\fIdirectory\fR" 7
.IX Item "--chdir=directory"
Change directory before processing files.  When multiple directories
are specified in \fB\-\-chdir\fR option, by using wildcard form or
repeating option, \fB\-\-glob\fR file expansion will be done for every
directories.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-chdir \*(Aq/usr/man/man?\*(Aq \-\-glob \*(Aq*.[0\-9]\*(Aq ...
.Ve
.IP "\fB\-\-readlist\fR" 7
.IX Item "--readlist"
Get filenames from standard input.  Read standard input and use each
line as a filename for searching.  You can feed the output from other
command like \fBfind\fR\|(1) for \fBgreple\fR with this option.  Next example
searches string from files modified within 7 days:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    find . \-mtime \-7 \-print | greple \-\-readlist pattern
.Ve
.Sp
Using \fBfind\fR module, this can be done like:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-Mfind . \-mtime \-7 \-\- pattern
.Ve
.SS "\s-1COLORS\s0"
.IX Subsection "COLORS"
.IP "\fB\-\-color\fR=\fIauto\fR|\fIalways\fR|\fInever\fR, \fB\-\-nocolor\fR" 7
.IX Item "--color=auto|always|never, --nocolor"
Use terminal color capability to emphasize the matched text.  Default
is `auto': effective when \s-1STDOUT\s0 is a terminal and option \fB\-o\fR is not
given, not otherwise.  Option value `always' and `never' will work as
expected.
.Sp
Option \fB\-\-nocolor\fR is alias for \fB\-\-color\fR=\fInever\fR.
.IP "\fB\-\-colormap\fR=\fIspec\fR" 7
.IX Item "--colormap=spec"
Specify color map.  Because this option is mostly implemented by
Getopt::EX::Colormap module, consult its document for detail and
up-to-date specification.
.Sp
Color specification is combination of single uppercase character
representing basic colors, and (usually brighter) alternative colors in
lowercase:
.Sp
.Vb 8
\&    R  r   Red
\&    G  g   Green
\&    B  b   Blue
\&    C  c   Cyan
\&    M  m   Magenta
\&    Y  y   Yellow
\&    K  k   Black
\&    W  w   White
.Ve
.Sp
or \s-1RGB\s0 value and 24 grey levels if using \s-1ANSI 256\s0 color terminal:
.Sp
.Vb 5
\&    (255,255,255)      : 24bit decimal RGB colors
\&    #000000 .. #FFFFFF : 24bit hex RGB colors
\&    #000    .. #FFF    : 12bit hex RGB 4096 colors
\&    000 .. 555         : 6x6x6 RGB 216 colors
\&    L00 .. L25         : Black (L00), 24 grey levels, White (L25)
.Ve
.RS 7
.Sp
.RS 4
Beginning # can be omitted in 24bit \s-1RGB\s0 notation.
.Sp
When values are all same in 24bit or 12bit \s-1RGB,\s0 it is converted to 24
grey level, otherwise 6x6x6 216 color.
.RE
.RE
.RS 7
.Sp
or color names enclosed by angle bracket:
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&    <red> <blue> <green> <cyan> <magenta> <yellow>
\&    <aliceblue> <honeydue> <hotpink> <mooccasin>
\&    <medium_aqua_marine>
.Ve
.Sp
with other special effects:
.Sp
.Vb 12
\&    N    None
\&    Z  0 Zero (reset)
\&    D  1 Double\-struck (boldface)
\&    P  2 Pale (dark)
\&    I  3 Italic
\&    U  4 Underline
\&    F  5 Flash (blink: slow)
\&    Q  6 Quick (blink: rapid)
\&    S  7 Stand\-out (reverse video)
\&    V  8 Vanish (concealed)
\&    X  9 Crossed out
\&    E    Erase Line
\&
\&    ;    No effect
\&    /    Toggle foreground/background
\&    ^    Reset to foreground
.Ve
.Sp
If the spec includes \f(CW\*(C`/\*(C'\fR, left side is considered as foreground color
and right side as background.  If multiple colors are given in same
spec, all indicators are produced in the order of their presence.  As
a result, the last one takes effect.
.Sp
Effect characters are case insensitive, and can be found anywhere and
in any order in color spec string.  Character \f(CW\*(C`;\*(C'\fR does nothing and
can be used just for readability, like \f(CW\*(C`SD;K/544\*(C'\fR.
.Sp
Example:
.Sp
.Vb 7
\&    RGB  6x6x6    12bit      24bit           color name
\&    ===  =======  =========  =============  ==================
\&    B    005      #00F       (0,0,255)      <blue>
\&     /M     /505      /#F0F   /(255,0,255)  /<magenta>
\&    K/W  000/555  #000/#FFF  000000/FFFFFF  <black>/<white>
\&    R/G  500/050  #F00/#0F0  FF0000/00FF00  <red>/<green>
\&    W/w  L03/L20  #333/#ccc  303030/c6c6c6  <dimgrey>/<lightgrey>
.Ve
.Sp
Multiple colors can be specified separating by white space or comma,
or by repeating options.  Those colors will be applied for each
pattern keywords.  Next command will show word `foo' in red, `bar' in
green and `baz' in blue.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-colormap=\*(AqR G B\*(Aq \*(Aqfoo bar baz\*(Aq
\&
\&    greple \-\-cm R \-e foo \-\-cm G \-e bar \-\-cm B \-e baz
.Ve
.Sp
Coloring capability is implemented in Getopt::EX::Colormap module.
.RE
.IP "\fB\-\-colormap\fR=\fIfield\fR=\fIspec\fR,..." 7
.IX Item "--colormap=field=spec,..."
Another form of colormap option to specify the color for fields:
.Sp
.Vb 4
\&    FILE      File name
\&    LINE      Line number
\&    TEXT      Unmatched normal text
\&    BLOCKEND  Block end mark
.Ve
.Sp
In current release, \f(CW\*(C`BLOCKEND\*(C'\fR mark is colored with \f(CW\*(C`E\*(C'\fR effect
recently implemented in Getopt::EX module, which allows to fill up
the line with background color.  This effect uses irregular escape
sequence, and you may need to define \f(CW\*(C`LESSANSIENDCHARS\*(C'\fR environment
as \*(L"mK\*(R" to see the result with less command.
.IP "\fB\-\-colormap\fR=\fI&func\fR" 7
.IX Item "--colormap=&func"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-colormap\fR=\fIsub{...}\fR" 7
.IX Item "--colormap=sub{...}"
.PD
You can also set the name of perl subroutine name or definition to be
called handling matched words.  Target word is passed as variable
\&\f(CW$_\fR, and the return value of the subroutine will be displayed.
.Sp
Next command convert all words in C comment to upper case.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-all \*(Aq/\e*(?s:.*?)\e*/\*(Aq \-\-cm \*(Aqsub{uc}\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
You can quote matched string instead of coloring (this emulates
deprecated option \fB\-\-quote\fR):
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-cm \*(Aqsub{"<".$_.">"}\*(Aq ...
.Ve
.Sp
It is possible to use this definition with field names.  Next example
print line numbers in seven digits.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-n \-\-cm \*(AqLINE=sub{s/(\ed+)/sprintf("%07d",$1)/e;$_}\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
Experimentally, function can be combined with other normal color
specifications.  Also the form \fI&func;\fR can be repeated.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-cm \*(AqBF/544;sub{uc}\*(Aq
\&
\&    greple \-\-cm \*(AqR;&func1;&func2;&func3\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
When color for '\s-1TEXT\s0' field is specified, whole text including matched
part is passed to the function, exceptionally.  It is not recommended
to use user defined function for '\s-1TEXT\s0' field.
.IP "\fB\-\-[no]colorful\fR" 7
.IX Item "--[no]colorful"
Shortcut for \fB\-\-colormap\fR='\fI\s-1RD GD BD CD MD YD\s0\fR' in \s-1ANSI 16\s0 colors
mode, and \fB\-\-colormap\fR='\fID/544 D/454 D/445 D/455 D/454 D/554\fR' and
other combination of 3, 4, 5 for 256 colors mode.  Enabled by default.
.Sp
When single pattern is specified, first color in colormap is used for
the pattern.  If multiple patterns and multiple colors are specified,
each patterns are colored with corresponding colors cyclically.
.Sp
Option \fB\-\-regioncolor\fR, \fB\-\-uniqcolor\fR and \fB\-\-colorindex\fR change
this behavior.
.IP "\fB\-\-colorindex\fR=\fIspec\fR, \fB\-\-ci\fR=\fIspec\fR" 7
.IX Item "--colorindex=spec, --ci=spec"
Specify color index method by combination of spec characters.
Meaningful combinations are \fBA\fR, \fBD\fR, \fB\s-1AB\s0\fR, \fB\s-1DB\s0\fR and \fBR\fR.
.RS 7
.IP "A (Ascending)" 4
.IX Item "A (Ascending)"
Apply different color sequentially according to the order of
appearance.
.IP "D (Descending)" 4
.IX Item "D (Descending)"
Apply different color sequentially according to the reversed order of
appearance.
.IP "B (Block)" 4
.IX Item "B (Block)"
Reset sequential index on every block.
.IP "R (Random)" 4
.IX Item "R (Random)"
Apply random color.
.IP "N (Normal)" 4
.IX Item "N (Normal)"
Reset to normal behavior.  Because the last option takes effect,
\&\fB\-\-ci=N\fR can be used to reset the behavior set by previous options.
.RE
.RS 7
.RE
.IP "\fB\-\-random\fR" 7
.IX Item "--random"
Shortcut for \fB\-\-colorindex=R\fR.
.IP "\fB\-\-ansicolor\fR=\fI16\fR|\fI256\fR|\fI24bit\fR" 7
.IX Item "--ansicolor=16|256|24bit"
If set as \fI16\fR, use \s-1ANSI 16\s0 colors as a default color set, otherwise
\&\s-1ANSI 256\s0 colors.  When set as \fI24bit\fR, 6 hex digits notation produces
24bit color sequence.  Default is \fI256\fR.
.IP "\fB\-\-[no]256\fR" 7
.IX Item "--[no]256"
Shortcut for \fB\-\-ansicolor\fR=\fI256\fR or \fI16\fR.
.IP "\fB\-\-[no]regioncolor\fR, \fB\-\-[no]rc\fR" 7
.IX Item "--[no]regioncolor, --[no]rc"
Use different colors for each \fB\-\-inside\fR/\fBoutside\fR regions.
.Sp
Disabled by default, but automatically enabled when only single search
pattern is specified.  Use \fB\-\-no\-regioncolor\fR to cancel automatic
action.
.IP "\fB\-\-[no]uniqcolor\fR, \fB\-\-[no]uc\fR" 7
.IX Item "--[no]uniqcolor, --[no]uc"
Use different colors for different string matched.
Disabled by default.
.Sp
Next example prints all words start by `color' and display them all in
different colors.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-uniqcolor \*(Aqcolou?r\ew*\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
When used with option \fB\-i\fR, color is selected in case-insensitive
fashion.  If you want case-insensitive match and case-sensitive color
selection, indicate insensitiveness in the pattern rather than command
option (e.g. \f(CW\*(C`(?i)pattern\*(C'\fR).
.IP "\fB\-\-face\fR=[\-+]\fIeffect\fR" 7
.IX Item "--face=[-+]effect"
Set or unset specified \fIeffect\fR for all color specs.  Use `+'
(optional) to set, and `\-' to unset.  Effect is a single character
expressing: S (Stand-out), U (Underline), D (Double-struck), F (Flash)
or E (Erase Line).
.Sp
Next example remove D (double-struck) effect.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-face \-D
.Ve
.Sp
Multiple effects can be set/unset at once.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-face SF\-D
.Ve
.Sp
Use `/' to set effect to background.  Only `E' makes sense to use in
background, though.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-face /E
.Ve
.SS "\s-1BLOCKS\s0"
.IX Subsection "BLOCKS"
.IP "\fB\-p\fR, \fB\-\-paragraph\fR" 7
.IX Item "-p, --paragraph"
Print a paragraph which contains the pattern.  Each paragraph is
delimited by two or more successive newlines by default.  Be aware
that an empty line is not a paragraph delimiter if which contains
space characters.  Example:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-np \*(Aqsetuid script\*(Aq /usr/man/catl/perl.l
\&
\&    greple \-pe \*(Aq^struct sockaddr\*(Aq /usr/include/sys/socket.h
.Ve
.Sp
It changes the unit of context specified by \fB\-A\fR, \fB\-B\fR, \fB\-C\fR
options.  Space gap between paragraphs are also treated as block
unit.  Thus, option \fB\-pC2\fR will print with previous and next
paragraph, while \fB\-pC1\fR will print with just surrounding spaces.
.Sp
You can create original paragraph pattern by \fB\-\-border\fR option.
.IP "\fB\-\-all\fR" 7
.IX Item "--all"
Treat entire file contents as a single block.  This is almost
identical to following command.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-block=\*(Aq(?s).*\*(Aq
.Ve
.IP "\fB\-\-border\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "--border=pattern"
Specify record block border pattern.  Default block is a single line
and use \f(CW\*(C`/^/m\*(C'\fR as a pattern.  Paragraph mode uses
\&\f(CW\*(C`/(?:\eA|\eR)\eK\eR+/\*(C'\fR, which means continuous newlines at the beginning
of text or following another newline (\f(CW\*(C`\eR\*(C'\fR means more general
linebreaks including \f(CW\*(C`\er\en\*(C'\fR; consult perlrebackslash for detail).
.Sp
Next command treat the data as a series of 10\-line unit.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-n \-\-border=\*(Aq(.*\en){1,10}\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
Contrary to the next \fB\-\-block\fR option, \fB\-\-border\fR never produce
disjoint records.
.IP "\fB\-\-block\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "--block=pattern"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-block\fR=\fI&sub\fR" 7
.IX Item "--block=&sub"
.PD
Specify the record block to display.  Default block is a single line.
.Sp
When blocks are not continuous and there are gaps between them, the
match occurred outside blocks are ignored.
.Sp
If multiple block options are supplied, overlapping blocks are merged
into single block.
.Sp
Please be aware that this option is sometimes quite time consuming,
because it finds all blocks before processing.
.IP "\fB\-\-blockend\fR=\fIstring\fR" 7
.IX Item "--blockend=string"
Change the end mark displayed after \fB\-pABC\fR or \fB\-\-block\fR options.
Default value is \*(L"\-\-\en\*(R".
.SS "\s-1REGIONS\s0"
.IX Subsection "REGIONS"
.IP "\fB\-\-inside\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "--inside=pattern"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-outside\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "--outside=pattern"
.PD
Option \fB\-\-inside\fR and \fB\-\-outside\fR limit the text area to be matched.
For simple example, if you want to find string `and' not in the word
`command', it can be done like this.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-outside=command and
.Ve
.Sp
The block can be larger and expand to multiple lines.  Next command
searches from C source, excluding comment part.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-outside \*(Aq(?s)/\e*.*?\e*/\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
Next command searches only from \s-1POD\s0 part of the perl script.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-inside=\*(Aq(?s)^=.*?(^=cut|\eZ)\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
When multiple \fBinside\fR and \fBoutside\fR regions are specified, those
regions are mixed up in union way.
.Sp
In multiple color environment, and if single keyword is specified,
matches in each \fB\-\-inside\fR/\fBoutside\fR regions are printed in
different colors.  Forcing this operation with multiple keywords, use
\&\fB\-\-regioncolor\fR option.
.IP "\fB\-\-inside\fR=\fI&function\fR" 7
.IX Item "--inside=&function"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-outside\fR=\fI&function\fR" 7
.IX Item "--outside=&function"
.PD
If the pattern name begins by ampersand (&) character, it is treated
as a name of subroutine which returns a list of blocks.  Using this
option, user can use arbitrary function to determine from what part of
the text they want to search.  User defined function can be defined in
\&\fI.greplerc\fR file or by module option.
.IP "\fB\-\-include\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "--include=pattern"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-exclude\fR=\fIpattern\fR" 7
.IX Item "--exclude=pattern"
.IP "\fB\-\-include\fR=\fI&function\fR" 7
.IX Item "--include=&function"
.IP "\fB\-\-exclude\fR=\fI&function\fR" 7
.IX Item "--exclude=&function"
.PD
\&\fB\-\-include\fR/\fBexclude\fR option behave exactly same as
\&\fB\-\-inside\fR/\fBoutside\fR when used alone.
.Sp
When used in combination, \fB\-\-include\fR/\fBexclude\fR are mixed in \s-1AND\s0
manner, while \fB\-\-inside\fR/\fBoutside\fR are in \s-1OR.\s0
.Sp
Thus, in the next example, first line prints all matches, and second
does none.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-inside PATTERN \-\-outside PATTERN
\&
\&    greple \-\-include PATTERN \-\-exclude PATTERN
.Ve
.Sp
You can make up desired matches using \fB\-\-inside\fR/\fBoutside\fR option,
then remove unnecessary part by \fB\-\-include\fR/\fBexclude\fR
.IP "\fB\-\-strict\fR" 7
.IX Item "--strict"
Limit the match area strictly.
.Sp
By default, \fB\-\-block\fR, \fB\-\-inside\fR/\fBoutside\fR,
\&\fB\-\-include\fR/\fBexclude\fR option allows partial match within the
specified area.  For instance,
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-inside and command
.Ve
.Sp
matches pattern \f(CW\*(C`command\*(C'\fR because the part of matched string is
included in specified inside-area.  Partial match fails when option
\&\fB\-\-strict\fR provided, and longer string never matches within shorter
area.
.Sp
Interestingly enough, above example
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-include PATTERN \-\-exclude PATTERN
.Ve
.Sp
produces output, as a matter of fact.  Think of the situation
searching, say, \f(CW\*(Aq PATTERN \*(Aq\fR with this condition.  Matched area
includes surrounding spaces, and satisfies both conditions partially.
This match does not occur when option \fB\-\-strict\fR is given, either.
.SS "\s-1CHARACTER CODE\s0"
.IX Subsection "CHARACTER CODE"
.IP "\fB\-\-icode\fR=\fIcode\fR" 7
.IX Item "--icode=code"
Target file is assumed to be encoded in utf8 by default.  Use this
option to set specific encoding.  When handling Japanese text, you may
choose from 7bit\-jis (jis), euc-jp or shiftjis (sjis).  Multiple code
can be supplied using multiple option or combined code names with
space or comma, then file encoding is guessed from those code sets.
Use encoding name `guess' for automatic recognition from default code
list which is euc-jp and 7bit\-jis.  Following commands are all
equivalent.
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&    greple \-\-icode=guess ...
\&    greple \-\-icode=euc\-jp,7bit\-jis ...
\&    greple \-\-icode=euc\-jp \-\-icode=7bit\-jis ...
.Ve
.Sp
Default code set are always included suspect code list.  If you have
just one code adding to suspect list, put + mark before the code name.
Next example does automatic code detection from euc-kr, ascii, utf8
and \s-1UTF\-16/32.\s0
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-icode=+euc\-kr ...
.Ve
.Sp
If the string "\fBbinary\fR" is given as encoding name, no character
encoding is expected and all files are processed as binary data.
.IP "\fB\-\-ocode\fR=\fIcode\fR" 7
.IX Item "--ocode=code"
Specify output code.  Default is utf8.
.SS "\s-1FILTER\s0"
.IX Subsection "FILTER"
.IP "\fB\-\-if\fR=\fIfilter\fR, \fB\-\-if\fR=\fI\s-1EXP\s0\fR:\fIfilter\fR" 7
.IX Item "--if=filter, --if=EXP:filter"
You can specify filter command which is applied to each files before
search.  If only one filter command is specified, it is applied to all
files.  If filter information include colon, first field will be perl
expression to check the filename saved in variable \f(CW$_\fR.  If it
successes, next filter command is pushed.
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&    greple \-\-if=rev perg
\&    greple \-\-if=\*(Aq/\e.tar$/:tar tvf \-\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
If the command doesn't accept standard input as processing data, you
may be able to use special device:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-if=\*(Aqnm /dev/stdin\*(Aq crypt /usr/lib/lib*
.Ve
.Sp
Filters for compressed and gzipped file is set by default unless
\&\fB\-\-noif\fR option is given.  Default action is like this:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-if=\*(Aqs/\e.Z$//:zcat\*(Aq \-\-if=\*(Aqs/\e.g?z$//:gunzip \-c\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
File with \fI.gpg\fR suffix is filtered by \fBgpg\fR command.  In that case,
pass-phrase is asked for each file.  If you want to input pass-phrase
only once to find from multiple files, use \fB\-Mpgp\fR module.
.Sp
If the filter start with \f(CW\*(C`&\*(C'\fR, perl subroutine is called instead of
external command.  You can define the subroutine in \fI.greplerc\fR or
modules.  \fBGreple\fR simply call the subroutine, so it should be
responsible for process control.
.IP "\fB\-\-noif\fR" 7
.IX Item "--noif"
Disable default input filter.  Which means compressed files will not
be decompressed automatically.
.IP "\fB\-\-of\fR=\fIfilter\fR" 7
.IX Item "--of=filter"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-of\fR=\fI&func\fR" 7
.IX Item "--of=&func"
.PD
Specify output filter which process the output of \fBgreple\fR command.
Filter command can be specified in multiple times, and they are
invoked for each file to be processed.  So next command reset the line
number for each files.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-of \*(Aqcat \-n\*(Aq string file1 file2 ...
.Ve
.Sp
If the filter start with \f(CW\*(C`&\*(C'\fR, perl subroutine is called instead of
external command.  You can define the subroutine in \fI.greplerc\fR or
modules.
.Sp
Output filter command is executed only when matched string exists to
avoid invoking many unnecessary processes.  No effect for option
\&\fB\-l\fR and \fB\-c\fR.
.IP "\fB\-\-pf\fR=\fIfilter\fR" 7
.IX Item "--pf=filter"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-pf\fR=\fI&func\fR" 7
.IX Item "--pf=&func"
.PD
Similar to \fB\-\-of\fR filter but invoked just once and takes care of
entire output from \fBgreple\fR command.
.SS "\s-1RUNTIME FUNCTIONS\s0"
.IX Subsection "RUNTIME FUNCTIONS"
.IP "\fB\-\-print\fR=\fIfunction\fR" 7
.IX Item "--print=function"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-print\fR=\fIsub{...}\fR" 7
.IX Item "--print=sub{...}"
.PD
Specify user defined function executed before data print.  Text to be
printed is replaced by the result of the function.  Arbitrary function
can be defined in \fI.greplerc\fR file or module.  Matched data is placed
in variable \f(CW$_\fR.  Filename is passed by \f(CW&FILELABEL\fR key, as
described later.
.Sp
It is possible to use multiple \fB\-\-print\fR options.  In that case,
second function will get the result of the first function.  The
command will print the final result of the last function.
.IP "\fB\-\-continue\fR" 7
.IX Item "--continue"
When \fB\-\-print\fR option is given, \fBgreple\fR will immediately print the
result returned from print function and finish the cycle.  Option
\&\fB\-\-continue\fR forces to continue normal printing process after print
function called.  So please be sure that all data being consistent.
.IP "\fB\-\-callback\fR=\fIfunction\fR(\fI...\fR)" 7
.IX Item "--callback=function(...)"
Callback function is called before printing every matched pattern with
four labeled parameters: \fBstart\fR, \fBend\fR, \fBindex\fR and \fBmatch\fR,
which corresponds to start and end position in the text, pattern
index, and the matched string.  Matched string in the text is replaced
by returned string from the function.
.IP "\fB\-\-begin\fR=\fIfunction\fR(\fI...\fR)" 7
.IX Item "--begin=function(...)"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-begin\fR=\fIfunction\fR=\fI...\fR" 7
.IX Item "--begin=function=..."
.PD
Option \fB\-\-begin\fR specify the function executed at the beginning of
each file processing.  This \fIfunction\fR have to be called from \fBmain\fR
package.  So if you define the function in the module package, use the
full package name or export properly.
.IP "\fB\-\-end\fR=\fIfunction\fR(\fI...\fR)" 7
.IX Item "--end=function(...)"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-end\fR=\fIfunction\fR=\fI...\fR" 7
.IX Item "--end=function=..."
.PD
Option \fB\-\-end\fR is almost same as \fB\-\-begin\fR, except that the function
is called after the file processing.
.IP "\fB\-\-prologue\fR=\fIfunction\fR(\fI...\fR)" 7
.IX Item "--prologue=function(...)"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-\-prologue\fR=\fIfunction\fR=\fI...\fR" 7
.IX Item "--prologue=function=..."
.IP "\fB\-\-epilogue\fR=\fIfunction\fR(\fI...\fR)" 7
.IX Item "--epilogue=function(...)"
.IP "\fB\-\-epilogue\fR=\fIfunction\fR=\fI...\fR" 7
.IX Item "--epilogue=function=..."
.PD
Option \fB\-\-prologue\fR and \fB\-\-epilogue\fR specify functions called before
and after processing.  During the execution, file is not opened and
therefore, file name is not given to those functions.
.IP "\fB\-M\fR\fImodule\fR::\fIfunction(...)\fR" 7
.IX Item "-Mmodule::function(...)"
.PD 0
.IP "\fB\-M\fR\fImodule\fR::\fIfunction=...\fR" 7
.IX Item "-Mmodule::function=..."
.PD
Function can be given with module option, following module name.  In
this form, the function will be called with module package name.  So
you don't have to export it.  Because it is called only once at the
beginning of command execution, before starting file processing,
\&\f(CW\*(C`FILELABEL\*(C'\fR parameter is not given exceptionally.
.PP
For these run-time functions, optional argument list can be set in the
form of \f(CW\*(C`key\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`key=value\*(C'\fR, connected by comma.  These arguments
will be passed to the function in key => value list.  Sole key will
have the value one.  Also processing file name is passed with the key
of \f(CW\*(C`FILELABEL\*(C'\fR constant.  As a result, the option in the next form:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    \-\-begin function(key1,key2=val2)
\&    \-\-begin function=key1,key2=val2
.Ve
.PP
will be transformed into following function call:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    function(&FILELABEL => "filename", key1 => 1, key2 => "val2")
.Ve
.PP
As described earlier, \f(CW\*(C`FILELABEL\*(C'\fR parameter is not given to the
function specified with module option. So
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    \-Mmodule::function(key1,key2=val2)
\&    \-Mmodule::function=key1,key2=val2
.Ve
.PP
simply becomes:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    function(key1 => 1, key2 => "val2")
.Ve
.PP
The function can be defined in \fI.greplerc\fR or modules.  Assign the
arguments into hash, then you can access argument list as member of
the hash.  It's safe to delete \s-1FILELABEL\s0 key if you expect random
parameter is given.  Content of the target file can be accessed by
\&\f(CW$_\fR.  Ampersand (\f(CW\*(C`&\*(C'\fR) is required to avoid the hash key is
interpreted as a bare word.
.PP
.Vb 7
\&    sub function {
\&        my %arg = @_;
\&        my $filename = delete $arg{&FILELABEL};
\&        $arg{key1};             # 1
\&        $arg{key2};             # "val2"
\&        $_;                     # contents
\&    }
.Ve
.SS "\s-1OTHERS\s0"
.IX Subsection "OTHERS"
.IP "\fB\-\-usage\fR[=\fIexpand\fR]" 7
.IX Item "--usage[=expand]"
\&\fBGreple\fR print usage and exit with option \fB\-\-usage\fR, or no valid
parameter is not specified.  In this case, module option is displayed
with help information if available.  If you want to see how they are
expanded, supply something not empty to \fB\-\-usage\fR option, like:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-Mmodule \-\-usage=expand
.Ve
.IP "\fB\-\-man\fR, \fB\-\-doc\fR" 7
.IX Item "--man, --doc"
Show manual page.
Display module's manual page when used with \fB\-M\fR option.
.IP "\fB\-\-show\fR, \fB\-\-less\fR" 7
.IX Item "--show, --less"
Show module file contents.  Use with \fB\-M\fR option.
.IP "\fB\-\-path\fR" 7
.IX Item "--path"
Show module file path.  Use with \fB\-M\fR option.
.IP "\fB\-\-norc\fR" 7
.IX Item "--norc"
Do not read startup file: \fI~/.greplerc\fR.
.IP "\fB\-\-require\fR=\fIfilename\fR" 7
.IX Item "--require=filename"
Include arbitrary perl program.
.IP "\fB\-\-conceal\fR \fItype\fR=\fIval\fR" 7
.IX Item "--conceal type=val"
Conceal runtime errors.  Repeatable.  Types are:
.RS 7
.IP "\fBread\fR" 4
.IX Item "read"
(Default 1) Errors occurred during file read.  Mainly unicode related
errors when reading binary or ambiguous text file.
.IP "\fBskip\fR" 4
.IX Item "skip"
(Default 0) File skip warnings produced when fatal error was occurred
during file read.  Occurs when reading binary files with automatic
character code recognition.
.IP "\fBall\fR" 4
.IX Item "all"
Set same value for all types.
.RE
.RS 7
.RE
.IP "\fB\-\-persist\fR" 7
.IX Item "--persist"
As \fBgreple\fR tries to read data as a character string, sometimes fails
to convert them into internal representation, and the file is skipped
without processing.  When option \fB\-\-persist\fR is specified, command
does not give up the file, and tries to read as binary data.
.Sp
Next command will show strings in binary file.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-o \-\-re \*(Aq(?a)\ew{4,}\*(Aq \-\-persist \-\-uc /bin/*
.Ve
.Sp
If you want read all files as binary data, use \fB\-\-icode=binary\fR
instead.
.IP "\fB\-Mdebug\fR, \fB\-d\fR\fIx\fR" 7
.IX Item "-Mdebug, -dx"
Debug option is described in App::Greple::debug module.
.SH "ENVIRONMENT and STARTUP FILE"
.IX Header "ENVIRONMENT and STARTUP FILE"
Environment variable \s-1GREPLEOPTS\s0 is used as a default options.  They
are inserted before command line options.
.PP
Before starting execution, \fIgreple\fR reads the file named \fI.greplerc\fR
on user's home directory.  Following directives can be used.
.IP "\fBoption\fR \fIname\fR string" 7
.IX Item "option name string"
Argument \fIname\fR of `option' directive is user defined option name.
The rest are processed by \fIshellwords\fR routine defined in
Text::ParseWords module.  Be sure that this module sometimes requires
escape backslashes.
.Sp
Any kind of string can be used for option name but it is not combined
with other options.
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&    option \-\-fromcode \-\-outside=\*(Aq(?s)\e/\e*.*?\e*\e/\*(Aq
\&    option \-\-fromcomment \-\-inside=\*(Aq(?s)\e/\e*.*?\e*\e/\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
If the option named \fBdefault\fR is defined, it will be used as a
default option.
.Sp
For the purpose to include following arguments within replaced
strings, two special notations can be used in option definition.
String \f(CW\*(C`$<n>\*(C'\fR is replaced by the \fIn\fRth argument after the
substituted option, where \fIn\fR is number start from one.  String
\&\f(CW\*(C`$<shift>\*(C'\fR is replaced by following command line argument and
the argument is removed from option list.
.Sp
For example, when
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    option \-\-line \-\-le &line=$<shift>
.Ve
.Sp
is defined, command
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-line 10,20\-30,40
.Ve
.Sp
will be evaluated as this:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-\-le &line=10,20\-30,40
.Ve
.IP "\fBexpand\fR \fIname\fR \fIstring\fR" 7
.IX Item "expand name string"
Define local option \fIname\fR.  Command \fBexpand\fR is almost same as
command \fBoption\fR in terms of its function.  However, option defined
by this command is expanded in, and only in, the process of
definition, while option definition is expanded when command arguments
are processed.
.Sp
This is similar to string macro defined by following \fBdefine\fR
command.  But macro expansion is done by simple string replacement, so
you have to use \fBexpand\fR to define option composed by multiple
arguments.
.IP "\fBdefine\fR \fIname\fR string" 7
.IX Item "define name string"
Define macro.  This is similar to \fBoption\fR, but argument is not
processed by \fIshellwords\fR and treated just a simple text, so
meta-characters can be included without escape.  Macro expansion is
done for option definition and other macro definition.  Macro is not
evaluated in command line option.  Use option directive if you want to
use in command line,
.Sp
.Vb 3
\&    define (#kana) \ep{InKatakana}
\&    option \-\-kanalist \-\-nocolor \-o \-\-join \-\-re \*(Aq(#kana)+(\en(#kana)+)*\*(Aq
\&    help   \-\-kanalist List up Katakana string
.Ve
.IP "\fBhelp\fR \fIname\fR" 7
.IX Item "help name"
If `help' directive is used for same option name, it will be printed
in usage message.  If the help message is `ignore', corresponding line
won't show up in the usage.
.IP "\fBbuiltin\fR \fIspec\fR \fIvariable\fR" 7
.IX Item "builtin spec variable"
Define built-in option which should be processed by option parser.
Arguments are assumed to be Getopt::Long style spec, and
\&\fIvariable\fR is string start with \f(CW\*(C`$\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`@\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`%\*(C'\fR.  They will be
replaced by a reference to the object which the string represent.
.Sp
See \fBpgp\fR module for example.
.IP "\fBautoload\fR \fImodule\fR \fIoptions\fR ..." 7
.IX Item "autoload module options ..."
Define module which should be loaded automatically when specified
option is found in the command arguments.
.Sp
For example,
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    autoload \-Mdig \-\-dig
.Ve
.Sp
replaces option "\fI\-\-dig\fR\*(L" to \*(R"\fI\-Mdig \-\-dig\fR", and \fIdig\fR module is
loaded before processing \fI\-\-dig\fR option.
.PP
Environment variable substitution is done for string specified by
`option' and `define' directives.  Use Perl syntax \fB\f(CB$ENV\fB{\s-1NAME\s0}\fR for
this purpose.  You can use this to make a portable module.
.PP
When \fIgreple\fR found \f(CW\*(C`_\|_PERL_\|_\*(C'\fR line in \fI.greplerc\fR file, the rest
of the file is evaluated as a Perl program.  You can define your own
subroutines which can be used by \fB\-\-inside\fR/\fBoutside\fR,
\&\fB\-\-include\fR/\fBexclude\fR, \fB\-\-block\fR options.
.PP
For those subroutines, file content will be provided by global
variable \f(CW$_\fR.  Expected response from the subroutine is the list of
array references, which is made up by start and end offset pairs.
.PP
For example, suppose that the following function is defined in your
\&\fI.greplerc\fR file.  Start and end offset for each pattern match can be
taken as array element \f(CW\*(C`$\-[0]\*(C'\fR and \f(CW$+[0]\fR.
.PP
.Vb 9
\&    _\|_PERL_\|_
\&    sub odd_line {
\&        my @list;
\&        my $i;
\&        while (/.*\en/g) {
\&            push(@list, [ $\-[0], $+[0] ]) if ++$i % 2;
\&        }
\&        @list;
\&    }
.Ve
.PP
You can use next command to search pattern included in odd number
lines.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    % greple \-\-inside \*(Aq&odd_line\*(Aq pattern files...
.Ve
.SH "MODULE"
.IX Header "MODULE"
You can expand the \fBgreple\fR command using module.  Module files are
placed at \fIApp/Greple/\fR directory in Perl library, and therefor has
\&\fBApp::Greple::module\fR package name.
.PP
In the command line, module have to be specified preceding any other
options in the form of \fB\-M\fR\fImodule\fR.  However, it also can be
specified at the beginning of option expansion.
.PP
If the package name is declared properly, \f(CW\*(C`_\|_DATA_\|_\*(C'\fR section in the
module file will be interpreted same as \fI.greplerc\fR file content.  So
you can declare the module specific options there.  Functions declared
in the module can be used from those options, it makes highly
expandable option/programming interaction possible.
.PP
Using \fB\-M\fR without module argument will print available module list.
Option \fB\-\-man\fR will display module document when used with \fB\-M\fR
option.  Use \fB\-\-show\fR option to see the module itself.  Option
\&\fB\-\-path\fR will print the path of module file.
.PP
See this sample module code.  This sample defines options to search
from pod, comment and other segment in Perl script.  Those capability
can be implemented both in function and macro.
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    package App::Greple::perl;
\&
\&    use Exporter \*(Aqimport\*(Aq;
\&    our @EXPORT      = qw(pod comment podcomment);
\&    our %EXPORT_TAGS = ( );
\&    our @EXPORT_OK   = qw();
\&    
\&    use App::Greple::Common;
\&    use App::Greple::Regions;
\&    
\&    my $pod_re = qr{^=\ew+(?s:.*?)(?:\eZ|^=cut\es*\en)}m;
\&    my $comment_re = qr{^(?:[ \et]*#.*\en)+}m;
\&    
\&    sub pod {
\&        match_regions(pattern => $pod_re);
\&    }
\&    sub comment {
\&        match_regions(pattern => $comment_re);
\&    }
\&    sub podcomment {
\&        match_regions(pattern => qr/$pod_re|$comment_re/);
\&    }
\&    
\&    1;
\&    
\&    _\|_DATA_\|_
\&    
\&    define :comment: ^(\es*#.*\en)+
\&    define :pod: ^=(?s:.*?)(?:\eZ|^=cut\es*\en)
\&    
\&    #option \-\-pod \-\-inside :pod:
\&    #option \-\-comment \-\-inside :comment:
\&    #option \-\-code \-\-outside :pod:|:comment:
\&    
\&    option \-\-pod \-\-inside \*(Aq&pod\*(Aq
\&    option \-\-comment \-\-inside \*(Aq&comment\*(Aq
\&    option \-\-code \-\-outside \*(Aq&podcomment\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
You can use the module like this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    greple \-Mperl \-\-pod default greple
\&
\&    greple \-Mperl \-\-colorful \-\-code \-\-comment \-\-pod default greple
.Ve
.PP
If special subroutine \fB\fBinitialize()\fB\fR is defined in the module, it is
called at the beginning with \f(CW\*(C`Getopt::EX::Module\*(C'\fR object as a
first argument.  Second argument is the reference to \f(CW@ARGV\fR, and you
can modify actual \f(CW@ARGV\fR using it.  See \fBfind\fR module as a sample.
